  },

  "resilience_assessment": {
    "failure_modes": [
      {
        "scenario": "A: Fraud detection service returns 503 for 5 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED BEHAVIOR: Every payment request hits the fraud service, waits up to 2s, gets a 503. With no circuit breaker, all 20 worker threads continue hammering the dead service. At 2s per failed request, effective throughput drops to ~10 req/s max (20 threads / 2s). If inbound rate exceeds this, requests queue and eventually timeout or get rejected. The service survives but is severely degraded for the full 5 minutes with no fast-fail path. SURVIVABILITY: PARTIAL — service stays up but all payments fail or are massively delayed. FIX: Add a circuit breaker to the fraud detection client (e.g., 3-failure threshold, 30s reset). Consider a fallback policy: either fail-open with increased post-payment fraud review, or fail-closed with a fast rejection (no 2s wait)."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "B: Database connection pool exhaustion for 30 seconds",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED BEHAVIOR: This is the most dangerous scenario. With no connection retry, any payment that completes the fraud check + Stripe charge but cannot write to the DB will either throw an exception or silently lose the transaction record. CRITICAL: if the Stripe charge has already been captured, the customer is charged but no record exists locally — a data integrity violation requiring manual reconciliation. During the 30s window, up to 20 concurrent requests could each charge Stripe successfully and then fail on DB write. SURVIVABILITY: FAILS — creates phantom charges with no local record. FIX: (1) Write to DB BEFORE calling Stripe (reserve/pending record), then update after Stripe confirms. (2) Add connection pool wait timeout with retry. (3) Implement an outbox pattern or write-ahead log so Stripe charges always have a corresponding local record. (4) Increase pool size — 10 connections for 20 threads is undersized."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "C: Stripe API latency increases to 8s for 10 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED BEHAVIOR: Requests succeed but take 8s each at Stripe. The circuit breaker does NOT trip because there are no failures — just slowness. With 20 worker threads each blocked for ~8s on Stripe (plus fraud check time + DB time ≈ ~9-10s total), throughput drops to ~2 req/s (20 threads / 10s). The worker pool saturates within seconds. New requests queue, then timeout or get rejected. This is a classic slow-dependency thread-pool starvation. The service appears to be up (health check passes) but is effectively dead for the full 10 minutes. SURVIVABILITY: FAILS — near-complete service outage despite Stripe technically working. FIX: (1) Add a separate thread pool or bulkhead for Stripe calls so they cannot starve the main worker pool. (2) Reduce Stripe timeout to 5s — an 8s payment API call is unlikely to produce a good user experience anyway. (3) Add an adaptive timeout or deadline propagation so slow requests are shed early. (4) Add a concurrency limiter for Stripe calls."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition to Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED BEHAVIOR: Stripe calls timeout after 10s each. After 5 consecutive failures, the circuit breaker opens. Timeline: first ~50s (5 × 10s timeouts to trip the breaker, though with 20 threads multiple failures happen concurrently, so it trips within ~10-20s). Once open, the circuit breaker fast-fails all Stripe calls for 60s. At 60s, it moves to half-open, lets one request through — which will timeout again (partition still active at T+60s). Breaker re-opens for another 60s. At T+120s, partition heals. Next half-open probe at ~T+130s succeeds, breaker closes, service recovers. SURVIVABILITY: SURVIVES with degradation — the circuit breaker does its job here, but the initial 10-20s window is painful (threads blocked on 10s timeouts). Total outage: ~2.5 minutes (2 min partition + ~30s recovery). FIX: (1) Reduce Stripe timeout to 5s to halve the initial pain window. (2) Lower circuit breaker threshold from 5 to 3 failures. (3) Queue failed payments for async retry rather than rejecting them outright."
      }
